In trade and contract law, a '''drop dead date''' is a provision added to a legal or trade act, such as a [[contract]] or a [[court order]].<ref name="Gotts2006">{{cite book|last=Gotts|first=Ilene Knable|title=The Merger Review Process: A Step-by-step Guide to U.S. and Foreign Merger Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5sZZbtC_cBYC&pg=PA84|accessdate=20 September 2017|year=2006|publisher=American Bar Association|isbn=9781590316528|page=84}}</ref> Such a provision sets a last-delay date (hence the name ''drop dead date'') past which certain consequences will automatically follow, such as cancelling the contract, taking [[property]] or entering a [[Legal judgment|judgment]].

In contract law, a typical drop dead date example is the contract for the baking of a birthday cake, where it is implied that a late delivery will constitute a material breach.

In German and Swiss Law, this is called a "Fixgeschäft".

