{{Infobox NRHP | name =Sonneborn Building | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes | image = Sonneborn bldg Baltimore.JPG | caption = Sonneborn Building March 2012 | location= 110 [[Baltimore-Washington Parkway|South Paca Street]], [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|17|11|N|76|37|21|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA | built = 1905 | architect = Pietsch, Theodore Wells | architecture = Classical Revival, Late 19th And Early 20th Century American Movements, Other, E. Industrial/Loft | added = October 29, 1982 | area = {{convert|0.6|acre}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 82001588<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} '''Sonneborn Building''', also known as Paca-Pratt Building, is a historic [[loft]] building in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], United States. Designed by [[Theodore Wells Pietsch I|Theodore Wells Pietsch]], it is a nine-story loft building constructed in 1905 of "fireproof" reinforced-concrete construction, faced in buff-colored brick, with a coursed ashlar foundation and stone trim. Its detailing reflects the Neoclassical Revival of the early 20th century. It was built for Henry Sonneborn and Company as a vertical clothing manufactory and was the tallest and largest strictly manufacturing building in the city of Baltimore.<ref name="mht_ihp">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-691.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Sonneborn Building|date=February 1982|accessdate=2016-04-01 |author=Dennis P. Dolan|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>
Sonneborn Building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1982. It is located in the [[Loft Historic District South]].<ref name="nris"/>
